article.headline: New Mexico 88, San Diego 75
article.story: ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- New Mexico had another good shooting night in The Pit and San Diego again came up empty on the road. Alfred Neale scored a season-high 24 points and had five of New Mexico's 15 3-pointers in an 88-75 win over the Toreros Tuesday night. New Mexico (8-4) has won six straight at home and six of seven overall since Dec. 8. The only loss in that stretch was at No. 5 Wake Forest (70-61) on Saturday. The Lobos have lost 19 games away from The Pit, a streak that stretches back to the 2001-02 season. But at home they are 8-2 this season. The Lobos have hit 31 3-pointers in their last two games in The Pit. and Neale, a junior college transfer, seems to especially thrive on the homecourt edge. "I'm really comfortable at home," Neale said after hitting 9 of 14 shots and going 5-for-8 on 3-pointers. "We do have difficulty on the road, but I think the environment of The Pit, with the fans behind us, gets our confidence going." New Mexico scored the game's first 11 points and put the game away with a 10-1 run in the second half after San Diego (3-12) had cut the Lobos' lead to 63-50 with 10:20 left. Brice Vounang led San Diego with 25 points, 23 of them in the second half. Reserve center Brandon Gay scored 24 for the Toreros, who are 0-11 on the road this season. San Diego has been hit hard by injuries this season and the list grew Tuesday when sophomore center Nick Lewis was knocked unconscious less than three minutes into the game. The 6-foot-10 sophomore was taken from the court on a stretcher. He was involved in a collision during a scramble for a loose ball with 17:45 left in the first half. Lewis was on the court on his back for about 10 minutes while being attended to by medical personnel. Lewis was taken to the University of New Mexico Hospital. Hospital spokesman Sam Giammo said Lewis was in satisfactory condition in the emergency room late Tuesday. After the game, San Diego coach Brad Holland said Lewis had sustained a concussion and was unconscious for a time. "When I went over to him, he was out cold," Holland said. "He was bleeding from his mouth. I think he was probably unconscious before he hit the floor." Holland said Lewis was undergoing a CAT scan at the hospital. "He had tingling in his lower extremities once he came to on the basketball court," Holland said. "He is moving around." San Diego is down to seven scholarship players and four walkons. "We started slow to begin with and then with Nick going down and everybody worried about him, we got off to an even slower start," Holland said. "We had to go to some zone and New Mexico did a great job. They hit eight 3s in the first half and opened up the game," he said. Vounang's eight straight points sparked an 11-2 run by the Toreros that got San Diego within 13 points in the second half. But New Mexico stretched the lead back up to 73-51 with a slam dunk and 3-pointer by Neale, a steal and layup by Danny Granger and a 3-pointer by Troy DeVries. Granger and DeVries, both transfers who became eligible on Dec. 21, again scored in double figures. Granger, the former standout at Bradley who transferred to New Mexico a year ago, scored 17 points and had 14 rebounds. Granger has averaged 20 points a game since joining the starting lineup. DeVries, a transfer from Portland State, had his fifth double-figure scoring game with 22 points, including six 3-pointers. The Lobos shot 55 percent in the first half and 51.6 percent for the game. "Our guys did a nice job tonight of taking what the defense gave us," New Mexico coach Ritchie McKay said. "We continue to read situations and defenses fairly well."
